  "relevant_summary": "Interventions reported for providing shelter habitats for amphibians include: creating artificial hibernacula or aestivation sites, which maintained great crested newt populations when implemented with other terrestrial habitat management, were used by common frog and smooth newts, and had four amphibian species recorded close to hibernacula at two of three sites [759]; creating refuges, including installing artificial refugia and reintroducing coarse woody debris, which helped maintain great crested newt populations when combined with other interventions, were used by translocated Hamilton\u2019s frogs and by hellbenders (with few used for breeding), and showed mixed effects of adding coarse woody debris on amphibian abundance and species number, with one restoration project increasing frog species following reintroduction of coarse woody debris [772]; leaving coarse woody debris in forests, which yielded mixed responses, including no significant differences in abundance for many species when debris was retained vs removed, higher use of clearcuts with debris retained by migrating amphibians, and higher survival of juvenile amphibians in piles of woody debris compared to open areas and similar to unharvested forest [843]; and creating refuge areas in aquatic habitats, for which no studies were found that directly tested effects on amphibian populations [813].",
